x4freetext: Same data given.
NIRR-1 is a low-power nuclear reactor,
which has highly enriched uranium as fuel, light
water as moderator and beryllium as reflector.
JAERI-Data/Code 2002-020. Curves and Tables of Neutron
Cross Sections in JENDL-3.3 Part 1 (Z=1-50), edited by
Tsuneo Nakagawa, Hiromitsu Kawasaki and Keiichi
Shibata, November 2002.JAERI (2002).
On the average the fast neutron flux density
was 1x10**11 n/cm2/s.
The irradiation was performed for one hour in
an inner irradiation channel (i.e.B2) of NIRR-1 due
to the relatively higher fast-to-thermal flux ratio.
The use of Al-0.1%Au foil (IRMM-530) as the
comparator and irradiation under Cd permits the
monitoring of the fast neutron flux via the
27Al(n,p)27Mg reaction and the epithermal neutron
flux via the 197Au(n,gamma)198Au reaction
simultaneously.
a horizontal dip-stick High-Purity Germanium
detector with a relative efficiency of 10% at 1332.5keV
gamma ray line, the MAESTRO emulation software
compatible with the ADCAMs multi-channel analyzer card,
associated electronic modules all made by EG&G ORTEC
and a personal computer.
The given uncertainties incorporate both
statistical and systematic uncertainties.
The main sources of uncertainties involved in
cross-section measurements were those associated with
the determination of fast neutron flux densities
and absolute decay rates.
